TEXT: Good day, ladies and gentlemen, and welcome to ALFA's First Quarter 2013 Earnings Conference Call.
At this time, all participants are in a listen only mode.
Later, we will conduct a question-and-answer session and instructions will be provided at that time.
As a reminder, today's conference is being recorded.
Now I would like to turn the conference over to Mr. Enrique Flores, vice president of corporate communications.
Mr. Flores, you may begin.
Thank you very much.
Good morning everybody and welcome to ALFA's first quarter 2013 conference call.
I would like to point out at that during this call we will be sharing forward-looking information with you and some statements which are based on the variables and assumptions that are uncertain.
Therefore, actual results could vary from those mentioned in this conference.
At this point, I would like to turn the call over to Mr. Ramon Leal, our CFO.
And good morning everyone.
We're very pleased with our first quarter results which were in line with our expectations.
Comparing our quarterly performance year-on-year, our total revenue increased 3% and EBITDA was 4% higher than in the first quarter of 2012.
We saw healthy volumes and revenue gains in all of our companies, except Alpek which reported at lower results against a very strong quarter last year.
The good news is that we're beginning to see improvements in Alpek's export markets.
I will give you more color on this later when I discussed our performance by individual business.
We continue to make significant investments in our business units to support future growth.
Capital expenditures in the quarter totaled $202 million.
Alphas cash flow generation in the quarter was strong.
This allowed us to maintain a very healthy financial condition despite our capital expenditures and the payment of the annual dividend to shareholders.
At the same time, Nemak tapped he international debt market, and debt capital markets for the first time extending the average life of its debt.
Moving on to the individual business units, as I just mentioned, market conditions are improving in Alpek's export markets, which gives us encouragement for the remainder of the year.
And though Alpek reported a year-over-year declines in revenues and EBITDA, we noticed a significant improvement on a sequential basis.
Against a very strong first-half 2012 backdrop, Alpek's first quarter 2013 sales volumes, revenues and EBITDA declined 6%, 4%, and 18% respectively when compared with the first quarter of 2012.
With improvements underway in the PTA and PET markets since November of last year, Alpek's revenue and EBITDA were up 9% and 13% respective on a sequential basis.
Alpek continues to invest to increase capacity marginally.
The bottleneck project at the Colombia site was completed in February and another one was initiated this past quarter at the Pearl River facility.

However, the most important news is that after evaluating different alternatives to enhance our low-cost installed PTA PET capacity in the North American region, this week we announced the signing of an IntegRex PTA license agreement and a PTA PET sourcing agreement with M&G group.
Under the agreements, M&G will license Alpek's IntegRex PTA technology for the construction of its new integrated PTA and PET plant in Corpus Christi, Texas.

In addition, Alpek will pay $350 million to M&G during the facility's construction and we'll receive contractual rights to 400,000 tons of PET made with 336,000 tons of PTA per year from the M&G facility.
Alpek will supply the raw materials for its portion of PTA PET under the agreement.

The combination of our IntegRex technology, the large-scale of the new integrated PTA PET plant in Corpus Christi and the region's energy and logistical advantages are expected to create one of the most competitive cost structures globally for PTA and PET.
On Nemak, we continue to be pleased with the performance.
Volume increased 12% year-over-year, sales were driven by the strength of the North American auto industry.
As a result, the Company sold 11.4 million equivalent units in the first quarter 2012.
Nemak's North American customer production was up 2% in the quarter.
In Europe, Nemak has been able to outperform the European industry trends as it has focused on customers that have been able to export engines and vehicles to other markets.
Revenue was up 14% and EBITDA was 18% higher than in the same period in the prior year.
Nemak achieved a higher EBITDA per unit has been in the first quarter 2012 thanks to productivity gains, a better product mix, and cost savings.
An important event for Nemak in the quarter was at the issuance of senior notes in the international markets for $500 million.
This was the first time that Nemak tapped the international capital markets for a 10-year tenure.
Proceeds were used for the prepayment of shorter life indebtedness.
As a result of this transaction, Nemak debt maturity was extended to 5.8 years from 2.7 years giving Nemak a more flexible capital structure to support its future growth plans.
At Sigma, results were in line with total volume increasing 3% in the quarter.
Volume gains were achieved in process meat and dairy products of 2% and 3% respectively.

The Company continued to add it to its product portfolio with the launch of a Greek style yogurt, a line of gourmet hotdogs under the San Rafael brand and Nutroys, ham snacks with fun shapes oriented to kids.
Sales volume growth in Mexico was up 3.6% better than industry sales which declined in the quarter.
This growth reflect the renewed marketing campaigns and commercial support for the category and new product launches.
We did see some increases in raw material prices but we were able to take price increases to offset this.
Revenue and EBITDA increased 5% and 8% respectively.

EBITDA margin increased 30 basis points from the prior year mainly due to higher sales and efficiencies in Mexico as well as higher profits in the US operations driven by a recent product mix and synergies from the Bar S acquisition.
Subsequent to the quarters end, Sigma acquired Comporacion de Empresas Monteverde, a leading cheese producer in Costa Rica.
Monteverde operates three plants in the country and has sales of $26 million in 2012.
The Company also exports products to Nicaragua, Panama, and El Salvador.
While Sigma's Costa Rica legacy cheese operations produce cheeses sold in bulk, Monteverde produces aged cheeses sold prepacked.
Therefore, the acquisition will allow Sigma to enhance its product and brand portfolio and increase its market share in Central America.

Alestra's ongoing transition to offering more value added and IT services for corporate clients and away from long distance services is delivering the desired results with revenue up 7% in the quarter.
Capacity for value-added services increased 26% year-on-year and represented 85% of Alestra's total sales.
EBITDA in the first quarter 2012 benefited from the consolation of provisions made for the interconnection rates and dispute making comparisons making it difficult for this year.
Excluding the one-time gain last year, EBITDA was up 54% in the first quarter of 2013.
Newpek, our oil and gas business had another good quarter as we continue to increase production and the mix continues to be liquids rich.

During the quarter, we connected 35 new liquid rich wells from the Eagles Ford Shale bringing total wells in production to 281 wells, more than double the number of producing wells we had in the same period of 2012.
As a result, we are now producing 6.5 thousand barrels of oil equivalent per day, up 51% from the first quarter 2012.
Newpek is still a small but rapidly growing business for us with revenue increasing 46% in the quarter, and EBITDA up 44%.

Before opening the call to questions, I would like to summarize our quarterly performance by reiterating that our first quarter results were in line with our expectations and have kept us on track to meet our previously disclosed guidance for the year.
We are optimistic about our performance for the rest of the year.
We will now take your questions.
Please, Enrique.
At this time, we would like to begin the Q&A session with questions on Alpek.

As you probably know, Alpek had its earnings conference call earlier this morning however Mr. Raul Millares, Alpek's CFO, is here with us and if there are any additional questions he will answer them.
Operator, please instruct the participants to Q4 questions on Alpek.
(Operator Instructions)
Okay, it seems that there are no further questions for Alpek then.
We will move forward and take questions on Nemak.
For that matter, Mr. Salvador Ramos, Nemak's CFO, is on the line and he will answer your questions.
Please place questions on Nemak.
(Operator Instructions).
We'll take our first question today from Christopher Vandergrift with Hartford Investment Management.
Congratulations on the strong quarter.
I was wondering if you could give more clarification on the North American and European segments and how strong the growth was and what you expect moving forward.
Yes indeed.
Christopher, I thank you for your question.
As you have heard, the industry in North America is evolving well.
Sales from a [baker's] perspective is a strong.
For several months it has been above the 15 million mark [vehicles].
And as a consequence, the demand of our product has been strong so we don't have any concerns on the demand from our customers.
In the case of Europe, there has been softening a little bit.
The German brands are strong.
They have been a little bit cut this quarter; however, engines are stable.
Engine production are stable and our volumes are a little bit lower of where it was a year ago, but not significantly below what we had in our guidance.
So you're still affirming the same guidance that you released previously of about $4,300 million for sales and $550 million for EBITDA?
yes, from a sales perspective, we believe in the $4.3 billion.
On the volume perspective, we continue considering the 46 million given in units and on the EBITDA perhaps it's going to be higher than the $565 million figure that we provide as a guidance.
And would that be driven by stronger currency or what would maybe drive the higher number?
It's the currency and also savings as explained by Mr. Ramon Leal.
Okay, and then it looks like the CapEx number was lower than what you guys had guided for and maybe I should hop back in queue, but it was like $57 million verse the $300 million you guided for.
Is that going to pick up throughout the year?

Yes, the guidance that we provided was $298 million, so essentially $300 million and what we have in the CapEx for the third quarter is below the average of this $300 million, but we continue seeing the $300 million that it could happen.
I'll hop back in queue.
Our next question today comes from Ivan Enriquez with HSBC.
Hello, Enrique, Ramon, and Salvador.
Thank you for the call and congratulations on the results especially on Nemak.
I think part of my question was already answered; just to make sure that I heard correctly, the volume you expect for 2013 in terms of [government entities] $46 million.
Is that right?
Right, Ivan.
And the breakdown of this volume in terms of the regions, what would it be?
Hold on, please.
The breakdown is close to [$29 million] in North America, close to [$4 million] in South America, [$12 million] in Europe, and slightly above [$1 million] in Asia.
And have you think of any capacity [additions] expansion plans or any other acquisition at sites?
No, normally we don't talk about acquisitions while we are analyzing them.
Last question, if I may.
Has the integration of the recently acquired JL French coming along?
Well, it has been very smooth, no surprises.
Both teams have integrated very well from many front lines.
The commercial area, the commercial, the operation and now we're working in the SAP area so everything has been working well.
Volumes are fine and EBITDA is higher than what we had in our business plan.
Okay, great.
You're welcome, Ivan.
Our next question comes from Marcos Duran with Scotiabank.
Good morning.

I was just wondering if you could give us a sense of the volume growth rate for the quarter excluding the JL French operations and then also if you could give us the capacity utilization rate in Mexico in particular.
Yes, so you want a comparison of the volume without French?
Yes, essentially, what we have is in the first quarter, our volume was 10.2 per quarter of last year and this year is 9.9.
And just on the capacity utilization rate in Mexico, could you give us a sense of where you are right now?
On average for Nemak is 85% for the quarter.
For Mexico is -- hold on, is for Monterrey is 90% and (inaudible) is at 84%.
We'll take our next question from Luis Miranda with Santander.
Please go ahead.
Yes, hi, good morning.
This is -- Salvador a specific question with regards to Mexico and operating costs.
We have seen some pressure in one of the OEM plants with regards to labor.
I don't know if you could tell what the status is in Mexico if you are Nemak if you are having any issue with regards to labor or with problems to maintain your workforce in the current operations.
Yes, thank you, Luis for your question.
No, you mean issues on labor in terms of hiring people or retaining them?
And wages, we saw Honda asking for a strike here, but I don't know if that's an isolated event or do you think its industry because of the high volumes that we are experiencing?
No, not an issue at all.
We continue working on certain productivity initiatives in order to release some people and to relocate them to some other initiatives while we invest in money for adding more value to the product.
But we don't have any issue on labor in the Mexican operation.
We are investing significantly a portion of our CapEx in Mexico.
Perfect.
Our next question comes from Luis Vallarino with Citi.
Good morning.
Thanks so much for the conference.
I have three questions.

The first one is if you could repeat maybe because I couldn't write it down, your volumes in Mexico and if you could give us an idea of how your exports are particularly in South America and maybe Brazil.
Secondly, on American and audible, and how sustainable is the EBITDA per head we saw this quarter.
We saw almost $12.5 per head.
That seems a bit high.
How sustainable is this for the rest of the year?
Maybe that's the reason you're expecting slightly higher EBITDA numbers are for the year?
And thirdly, if you're CapEx is also running a bit higher than expected initially.
On the third question, you said the volumes from Mexico, what proportion is exported.
And maybe if you can give some color on the exports to South America which is running some --
From Mexico to South America?
Just a minor fraction, perhaps there is just one program.
As far as I remember was just a minor fraction of the volume goes from Mexico to South America.

As far as I remember from quotation, right now customers have (inaudible) to deliver product for Mexico to Brazil because of the real appreciation and the economy there, but essentially I would say it's just a minor volume we deliver, but I don't have the figure right away.
But we can send it to you, Luis Vallarino.
I will take the note here.
And is it your EBITDA perhaps sustainable at the current level?
The level of what?
At these current levels.
The level that we saw in the first quarter was pretty good first quarter overall in terms of EBITDA per head.
Is this sustainable for the rest of the year?
Yes, yes indeed.
We expect better EBITDA per pace in the second quarter because we do expect a stronger volume in the second quarter.
So as a consequence from that, the EBITDA per pace is going to be stronger.

And there will be the seasonality effect in the third and fourth quarter but it's going to be up to now the figure that we have is going to be beyond the 11 million figure, the 11 million unit each quarter.
Got it.
In line with this may be to achieve these improvements, will we see a higher EBITDA and then what you are guiding at the beginning of the year?
So maybe in the order of $200 million or what would be your idea on CapEx for here?
Now, on the CapEx on the $300 million.
$300 million yes, sorry, sir.
And finally, one final question.
We are seeing now and maybe this question for Alpek also, we are seeing gas prices slightly higher now mandated by the government in Mexico because of these restrictions with the gas imports.
How does this affect you?
How hedged are you?
How can you offset these increases?

In the particular case of Nemak at the most recent threat that we have on the impact of a potential alternative, it could have an impact to of $1 million to $1.5 million on EBITDA if we don't do anything on a monthly basis.
On a monthly basis?
Got it.
On a monthly basis for the Mexican operation.
Got it.
So the $600 million of, sorry your $560 million of your current guidance, the improvement in the operations more than offset this potential increase of $1.5 million in costs per month?
Yes, you are right.
And I don't know if someone else wants to answer from Alpek.
You mentioned Alpek.
I already asked the question during the conference call.
Thanks so much.
Alpek has already answered that question, Salvador.
Okay, that's fine.
Thank you so much, (inaudible).
There are no further questions at this time.
Then we shall move to take questions on Sigma.
Mr. Ricardo Duenez, Sigma's CFO, is on the line and he will take care of your questions.
Please, queue for questions on Sigma.
(Operator Instructions).
We take our first question from (inaudible) with Nomura.
Just a couple of housekeeping items here.
Could you give me an update on the cash balance, the upcoming debt maturity schedule, and if there were any plans to address these refinancing needs in 2013.
Our maturity schedule looks like we have $220 million due in '14, $580 million due in '18, and $250 million due in '19.
We will obviously take a look at refinancing the '14 $220 million due.
That will probably take place towards the summer of this year.
And on a cash basis, nowadays were towards the end of the first quarter we have a cash position of about $120 million.
(Operator Instructions).
There appear to be no additional questions on that topic at this time, sir.
Good.
Then let's move forward and take questions on Alestra.
Here with us is Mr. Bernardo Garcia, Alestra's CFO, will take those questions.
(Operator Instructions)
There appear to be no questions on this topic either, sir.
Good.
We shall move to the final segment of our Q&A session, and we will take questions on Newpek.
Dr. Juan Luis San Jose is here with us and he will take questions on Newpek.
We do have a question from Marimar Torreblanca with UBS, please go ahead.
This question has been asked in other calls and meetings but I was just hoping there is an update.
You have any numbers on potential or proven research for the formations where you're currently operating?
Yes, we have proven reserves that we exchange with our banks and I don't have them in my head the proven reserves, perhaps our people in Dallas -- are you connected to Jose Luis?
Luis.
So December 31st, we have the latest report.
We have a total prove reserves of 4.4 million barrels plus 41.4 bcfs of gallons.
Billions?
Yes, billions.
And 1.46 million gallons of (inaudible).

That is just the proven reserves part and to be very clear, the proven reserve part out of the total resource that we expect to extract out of the Eagle Ford drilling program in the next years is just a very small portion still.
So we are still in the initial stages of the development.

We have just recently finished holding our acreage by production and we could say that we are just beginning the development phase of the program and these proven reserves are just a small sample of the total resource that is going to be produced.
Thank you, [Rodolfo].
Is there any way to know how smaller this portion is?
So if it's 10% or 5% of what you think the total plan holds?
Well, if you consider that we have 281 wells, we plan to drill between 1,500 and 1,700 locations.
So you can perhaps use that as an estimate.
Will take our next question today from Javier Santiago with Scotiabank.
Please go ahead.
Good morning.
I was wondering if you could please give us an update on the (inaudible) venture and also along the same lines my other question is about the energy reform coming up in Mexico.
What's the Company's outlook for the energy reform?
If you can talk about that, I'd appreciate it.
Well, the energy reform is still in the air.
It's not -- there're not a lot of light in what it might include.
Just a [near] sent to the Senate of the plan that they are thinking.
It's very conceptual.
So it's not -- -- it is not clear what the energy reform might include.
So anything that we will say will be speculative.
And you wanted also to know what we're doing in Mexico?
We received the assets, (inaudible) assets, and what place, in March 15, and the other in March 21.
Immediately we started working and implementing our plans.
Will need to wait at least six months to see the actual results of the implementation.
Okay, great.
Our next question comes from Nikolaj Lippmann with Morgan Stanley Smith Barney.
Please go ahead.
Quick question similar to the prior question I'm afraid.
Could you give us a sense of whether you are studying any particular projects especially if you can comment on what's going on in [Chacontepec]?
I understand that Pemex looking for private investment in some of Chacontepec.
Thanks
We are studying Chacontepec.
So this is still in the process of analyzing.
It will be of interest and we can provide value-added in Chacontepec, but we are active in analyzing Chacontepec.
In terms of size, would you think that that would it be roughly investments of $20 million or more (inaudible)?
It's larger but right now it will be premature to give you a figure.
(Operator Instructions).
We will move next to Ivan Enriquez with HSBC.
Hello again.
Can you please give us guidance in terms of the number of wells that you plan to have in production in the Eagle Ford Shale by the end of the year, hopefully also in 2014?

Well, we have 10 weeks our efficiency is on the average of 11 wells per week, per year, so we should drill around 110 wells during the year, but if we encounter difficulties in one well we might reduce that figure or if our efficiency with the [pad] drilling continues, we could hit 120.
The plan for 213 of wells put production, it's 131.
We are little bit ahead right now.

We are in the first quarter and that's why there is alter slightly better than not and we believe that next year to the number should be around that same range between 120 and 140 wells put to production.
But Jose Luis and that implies that we will increase rigs.
No, that's exactly the plan that we have for this year with 10 rigs running.
So the answer might be 110 for this year, additional 110 and 120 or 140 in the next year, right?
(Operator Instructions).
Let us move forward and see if there are questions on Alpha as a whole or corporate matters and Mr. Ramon Leal and myself will take care of such questions.
Will take our next question from [Ricardo Fernandez] with [Lenden Partners].
Please go ahead.
Good morning.
The question relates back to Newpek.

You mentioned a number of new wells to be drilled but is it safe to say that the production per well for your current 6500 barrels per day -- -- what's the growth rate of that given the number of wells your drilling per year in the next one or two years?
The drilling provides an increased new volume with existing wells have the declination so you have to add it declination of the existing wells plus the additional production.
So we will have some growth in the year but not as this quarter because in this quarter we put into production wells that were in the inventory.
And in terms of pricing, are you selling forward any production?
Are you hedging it, or is it all going to spot market?
How does that work?
We are not hedging so basically we would sell at the spot market.
Thank you very much.
(Operator Instructions).
We've move next to Marimar Torreblanca with UBS.
Please go ahead.

Let me take care of your first question.
This is Enrique Flores.
We reported this quarter some additional income coming from the disposal of certain assets at the private company level as well as at the level of other service companies.
And that's most of the explanation.
It is a cash income, but it's not recurrent.
And with respect to the financing costs I think we've done some work with respect to refinancing several of our business units.
I think you should expect that the cost of financing going forward potentially the same and we hope to lower it if market conditions and interest rates continue to be low.
